references: In Table I, we present a summarized comparison on the numerical simulation results to verify the effectiveness and efficiency of the developed method. In particular, we set T=1500𝑇1500T=1500, U=500𝑈500U=500, P=250𝑃250P=250, and η=1​e−4𝜂1𝑒4\eta=1e-4. The expected gradient norm is calculated upon a predetermined sample set, which is comprised by samples that are uniformly collected during the learning model’s training process when τ=1𝜏1\tau=1. In addition, the expected gradient norm is calculated whenever the model’s average parameters (i.e., θ¯ksubscript¯𝜃𝑘\bar{\theta}_{k}) are updated, and its final value is averaged across the entire training process of the corresponding learning model. In Table I, we present the performance of FIRL with different local updates in a period. The notation “τ=10∼15𝜏10similar-to15\tau=10\sim 15” denotes that the numbers of local updates from agents are uniformly distributed between 101010 and 151515. We can observe a trend that the learning model’s error convergence bound will increase as the number of local updates τ𝜏\tau increases, which is consistent with our previous discussions. In Table I, we also present the performance of FIRL under the consensus-based method (i.e. FIRL_C). On the premise of strong connectivity, the topology of agents’ network with μ2=1.4384subscript𝜇21.4384\mu_{2}=1.4384 is constructed by 3∼4similar-to343\sim 4 random connections from each agent to nearby collaborators, while these connections are increased to 4∼6similar-to464\sim 6 when μ2=2.5188subscript𝜇22.5188\mu_{2}=2.5188. Note that there is only one connection between any pair of agents. We can observe that being consistent with the conclusions in T1, the error convergence bound of targeted model is decreased when the local interactions are considered, even when the delay in local updating is taken into account (i.e., in case τ=1∼10𝜏1similar-to10\tau=1\sim 10). In addition, the topology with either a larger μ2subscript𝜇2\mu_{2} (i.e., more connections) or more local interactions (i.e., greater e𝑒e) generally obtains better training performance. Compared to FIRL with τ=10𝜏10\tau=10, FIRL_C with τ=10𝜏10\tau=10 requires the same amount of resource cost in FL, and although there are more resources required in local interactions, its expected gradient norm is lower. Thus, the system utility value can be also declined when W1subscript𝑊1W_{1} and W2subscript𝑊2W_{2} are small in FIRL_C.
